Memory Forensics > [T2]: Exploring Processes' Parent-child relationship

(2) Parent-child relationship: PSTREE

Parent-child relationships between processes refer to the connection between two or more processes where one process launches another. This connection forms a tree-like structure called a process tree, a hierarchical representation of running processes on a computer.

Processes with a parent-child relationship share data and instructions stored in memory during program execution. The parent process can monitor and control the 'child' process.

The 'pstree' plugin analyzes memory dumps by inspecting "PsActiveProcessHead" list like 'pslist' and then visualizes the parent-child relationships between processes, with each process represented as a node on the tree.

You can use this information to trace the execution path of a process and identify any malicious activity. For example, when a user opens a malicious word file, the legit word.exe process will spawn another malicious child process to perform evil actions (usually cmd.exe or powershell.exe).


pstree - zoom in

 

Let's look at the following example:

  1. The processes "ShellExperienc" and "WmiPrvSE" have a parent process ID of 772. By locating the process with ID 772, you can identify the process that spawned the two processes above.
  2. You will find that the process "svchost.exe" has the ID 772, indicating that it spawned the "ShellExperienc" and "WmiPrvSE" processes (i.e., svchost.exe is the parent process).

The pstree plugin simplifies the correlation by using dot indentation. The parent process, "services.exe," the top parent process, is represented by one dot. The child process, "svchost.exe," is represented by two dots, and three dots represent the child of the child process, "WmiPrvSE.exe."

Here are a few real examples of malicious links: 

  • A web browser (e.g., chrome.exe) spawning a suspicious child process (e.g., mshta.exe)
  • An email client (e.g., outlook.exe) spawning a suspicious child process (e.g., regsvr32.exe)
  • svchost.exe is running under a process other than services.exe
  • A system process (e.g., services.exe) spawning a client-side application process (e.g., calc.exe)
  • Windows explorer process (explorer.exe) spawning system process (e.g., lsass.exe)

The thing to highlight is that most malicious processes are spawned by a parent process that usually belongs to a client-side application (e.g., browser, mail client, and Office). Client-side applications are a primary delivery channel through which attackers deliver the malicious payload. Ultimately, they need the user to trigger the exploit by opening a file or a link.

The verbose mode of PSTREE (-v) lists detailed information about the running process, such as:

  • Audit: shows the full path to the application on disk. An application running from an unusual location should be considered suspicious. 
    • Most system applications reside under C:\Windows\System32\.
    • Users programs run from C:\Users\<User>\Appdata\, C:\Program Files x86\, or C:\Program Files\. So applications running from different paths are worth investigating.
  • Cmd: shows the command line used to start the process. Look for processes with suspicious command lines, such as:
    • powershell.exe running an encoded command.
    • svchost.exe executed without the (-k) parameter. The reason that legit "svchost.exe" execution always has a "-k" parameter is to allow the Service Control Manager to keep track of running services and manage them effectively.
  • Path: like the audit field, it shows the full path to the application on disk. The pstree uses two methods to extract paths of the application, as some malware can disguise itself by changing its path, as explained here. You may look for a path mismatch between the values of the "path" and "audit" fields.

'pstree -v' - zoom in

To sum up, you, as an analyst, can go through the following checklist when you run the pstree plugin to discover anomalies:

  • Run the pstree plugin to check processes relationships and look for:Processes that have cmd or PowerShell as child processes.
  • System processes (e.g., services.exe) that have a client-side application as their parent (e.g., explorer.exe).
  • Client-side application processes (e.g., calc.exe) which have a system process as their parent (e.g., service.exe)
  • Run pstree with -v option and look for:System applications that are running from a location other than C:\Windows\System32\, such as the 'Desktop' and 'Downloads' folders.
  • Client-side applications that are running from C:\Windows, or weird folder names.
  • Unusual long commands (e.g., a three lines command, usually encoded command.). Also, commands with abnormal arguments such as IP address, port number, or URL.
  • A mismatch between the values of the "path" and "audit" fields.
